            <lem>pakviAnnira</lem>
                    <note><!--9. pakviannira: Cohen Stuart proposes the alternative reading pakdiannira (see the Verbeteringen on the last page). --></note>
                  </app>
                  <app loc="10">
                    <lem>tamvā</lem>
                    <note>I would rather think tahva, but there is a stroke which probably distinguishes m from h. <seg rend="check">Split tamvāh uraṁ?</seg></note>
                  </app>
                  <app loc="11">
                    <lem>caruA</lem>
                    <note>thus Sarkar; vanua Cohen Stuart. The irrealis form carva is attested in Dharma Pātañjala, f. 68v, in the phrase yan carva ri saṅ hyaṅ ‘if they are to be sacrificed to the gods’, which confirms Sarkar’s reading in elegant fashion.</note>
                  </app>
